article.headline: Saint Louis 62, Rhode Island 58
article.story: ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Another big game from Tommie Liddell helped Saint Louis shake off a rough start in the Atlantic-10. Liddell scored all but seven of his 23 points in the second half of a 62-58 victory over Rhode Island on Wednesday night. The junior has scored 51 points the last two games. "Tommie's playing tremendous offensively and very good defensively," coach Brad Soderberg said. "With the addition of the 3-point shot to his arsenal he is really a load offensively. "That's the mark of a guy that can keep playing after college." Kevin Lisch added 14 points and seven assists for Saint Louis (11-5, 1-2 Atlantic 10), which had lost consecutive conference games for the first time since joining the Atlantic 10 a year ago. The Billikens lost to Duquesne on Saturday and St. Bonaventure before that, both sub-.500 teams, damaging their postseason aspirations. "That's why you recruit good kids, because every year something goes haywire," Soderberg said. "If you have a bunch of knuckleheads it can go right down the toilet. These kids are good people." The Billikens, who also got 11 points and six rebounds from Ian Vouyoukas, are 3-0 against Rhode Island (9-8, 2-1) since the move. Will Daniels had 15 points and eight rebounds for Rhode Island, held to a season low for points. He blew a dunk with a chance to cut the Rams' deficit to one with 13 seconds to go. "I was pretty shocked," Lisch said. "That ball went real high." Saint Louis was 5-for-6 at the free throw line in the final 26 seconds to put the game away. Dwayne Polk hit the second of two with 10 seconds left for a four-point lead and Lisch clinched it with a pair with 1.7 seconds to go. The Rams, who lead the conference with a 77-point average, shot a season-worst 32.8 percent. Jimmy Baron added 14 points for the losers. Saint Louis was 11-for-28 from 3-point range, one off its season best. Liddell was 5-for-8 from long range. "Against Bonny, against Duquense, they didn't do that," coach Jim Baron said. "They would have beaten both teams." The Billikens committed 14 turnovers, but had only one in the final 13:30 after Soderberg lambasted his players during a timeout. "They reacted to my challenge," Soderberg said. "I think they played hard, real hard." Rhode Island made only four of its first 22 shots in an error-filled first half, but finished on a 10-2 run for a 23-21 lead. Saint Louis had a chance to tie it but Polk missed two free throws with a half-second to go. The Rams shot 28 percent for the half and Saint Louis was at 30 percent, the teams combining to go 4-for-22 from 3-point range. "I was really surprised we were up two," Baron said. "We had a chance. They did the things they needed to do down the stretch."
